text: Man, I really like this concept... for the first minute, the 2ed half of this turns it into a generic slasher movie with a unique pov, but the beginning, now that has potential. Now, imagine if, instead of entering the chat, and killing them the owners face is revealed, and it's someone they know, either a school teacher or a parent or something. Probably a dad it works better as a parent.  Now, instead of being a generic slasher, it ends up being a moral quandary:  "there is no way that's my dad." "We need to call the police." text: I just saw The Incredibles 2. It was pretty enjoyable, a freshing and familiar throwback to days gone by.  I don't think it should be marketed as a children's movie however, as there are a few scenes that make me think that the PG rating wasn't quite right, such as the scene where Mr Incredible calls a coloured gentleman the N-word, and then then went on a 15 minute, explosive and explicit rant on how black people contribute the most to gun violence statistics in the United States. Yeah, not sure what the director was thinking.  Another odd scene was in the final battle between the Incredible family and the Underminer. The Underminer knocks over an embassy of a middle eastern country, and turns to screen and roars 'SYRIA IS ISREAL' , which was a little off, but only made stranger by the fact that he repeated it for 13 and a half minutes. Guess they just ran out of lines idk.  Speaking of running out of lines, the scene where Mr Incredible lynches Frozone didn't need to last 20 minutes. It was pretty graphic as well.  Overall, it was enjoyable, 7/10

text: Do to my research and studies, it's basically all about information and very interesting odd stuff. If you ever have seen the science poster of the iceberg sitting in the middle of the ocean with like 30% of the iceberg above the surface and the other 70% is below the surface. That is same representation of the internet. Now you can ask Google almost anything about any information at all. But the scary thing is about that, just like with the iceberg, Google will only tell you a small portion of information compared to the deep web. Now the deep web is not only about information but contains very "dark" things that the average human being should not be apart of. It's the online black market. Yes it contains child pornography, child abuse, illegal weapons, drugs, hitmen and assassinations, human trafficking, kidnappings, very weird games ect..... If your interested be my guest but I will say I wouldn't not go on the deep web with just some $300 average apple laptop. You do that you are in fact taking an extremely high risk of getting tracked from your IP address. Who ever goes on there, for the 98% of people that go on there are not there for a good reason. The other 2% are people that are just curious about it and that's when shits not looking good for you sorry but do research before you go into something like that, there are some crazy people who will do some crazy things just for the fun of it and very easy to get your location so be careful.

text: Stephen Susco, what the actual fuck are you doing. Not going on about the god awful acting happening here, but this is a gross misrepresentation of the dark web and IS ACTUALLY FUCKING DANGEROUS. To start off with, the program showing the cave lit with torches while the man screams "DuDe thIs iS DaRK WEb" is not only hilariously bad, it also makes it seem as though its some sort of all in one program, almost game like even. The attempt at making it seem scary with the dude's five second rambling is weak and is the most rough and crude, inaccurate presentation of it I've yet to see outside of creepy pastas. While yes, there's plenty of drug trafficking, child abuse, human trafficking, hitmen, and torture, it is not accessible to all. You have to know exactly where to look using various tools or spending hours upon hours going from dead site or some random message board and the like, and maybe then you'll find something of the sorts. There's plenty more on what the dark web is, but jesus christ if your entire movie revolves around a premise explain it better. Legitimately just say it's all the unlisted websites you can't find on search engines or with a normal browser and there you go. But my main concern is safety.  Commonly, when going on the dark web you want to have a few things set up. Obviously a Tor browser is required, but many suggest using a VPN, a virtual machine (basically running a computer inside your computer), scrambling your ip, or all of these just to be safe. Someone around my age, 17-20, should know what this stuff is or at least how to set it up, but this is where my BIGGEST concern lies. Kids nowadays often accompany or find a way to watch horror movies as it is a growing genre, and while anyone can be influenced, kids can be the most. Take for example the Ouji movies. Before they had came out, they weren't niche but they weren't well known at all, but immediately after you had thousands and thousands of kids and teens trying to buy something they thought would haunt them. I can almost guarantee that after this movie comes out, there's going to be lord knows how many kids or unprotected people will be trying to access the deep web, unaware that, while rare, the dangers like being kidnapped or hacked or killed can actually happen. God I just know there will be a "DEEP WEB CHALLENGE" soon, and when shit hits the fan these people will be to blame.

Just REBOOT AND DELETE ALL THE FILES FROM THE LAPTOP. Gosh. And if that's not enough then go to the police and what idiot actually takes someone's laptop like I mean it would be obvious people have stuff in there computer/laptop so like why take it in the first place. This movie was really undetailed and idiotic. I give it a 5/10  edit edit: Also Also, They should have a storyline behind it, unfriended 1 had where Laura Barns committed suicide and stuff but this time its a guy who works at a cafe and then looks in the lost and found and sees 'OH THERE'S A LAPTOP WHY NOT JUST STEAL IT, IT PROBABLY HAS NOTHING IN IT!111 I'LL BE SAFE!! ;DD' like they just talk about a guy stealing a laptop and it has files that are creepy and has some 'dark web' stuff on it but technically speaking he stole someone's laptop so he would be in trouble as well and the owner of the laptop would be as well. The movie could've ended way quicker if he wasn't dumb enough to get a laptop without second thoughts. They should've made it where Blaire and her friends ghost's would haunt them and kill them like all over again, but of course, they just make it where they think they know dark web. dUdEe ThIs iS dArKKkKkkk WwEbB!111   edit edit edit edit edit edit: (sorry for so many edits )x) When you have dark web you need browsers like TOR and others, you can't just have automatic files on your laptop. He would probably have to search that up on the hidden wiki or some stuff, (I don't know everything about dark web, and btw I don't go on it I just know stuff about it, don't ask)  and then find some links or something and find some videos. Another thing is DEEP WEB AND DARK WEB ARE 2 DIFFERENT THINGS. Deep web is things that are not accsessibale in the search engine, for example being on your Youtube account, thats deep web, but thats not a serious thing. Deep web is basically things that are secured and sometimes have passwords like Facebook, Reddit, etc. The dark web is any Web-like network that uses proprietary protocols or requires special software to access. text: I want to clear things up. If you browse the dark web, ISIS or some other group will not come over to your house and cut your penis off. Most .onion sites are scams. Anyone can create an .onion site claiming anything. So if you see a John Wick on the dark web offering to shoot anyone its probably a scam. Human trafficking, snuff (video showing the murder of someone), cannibalism, necrophilia, legit murder for hire and legit narcotics are things that are extremely rare and hard to find on Tor. Scam/honeypot sites 'selling' or 'offering' narcotics, fake everything (ID's, passports, money), firearms, and child porn are much more common. Red rooms are probably not real. The dark web isn't scary, its honestly kinda boring. Lots of broken links.
